It is a burn- ing zeal for the glory of Christ-..the welfare of his Church--and the salva- tion of precious souls, which alone can conduct a man through the work of a Reformer. Gerson retired to Lyons in the prime of life, probably out of disgust at what he had witnessed in the discharge of his public functions, or through vexation for having taken part against Jerom and Huss, raised up in Bohemia to proclaim the kingdom of God, and revive again the conso- lations of grace and the righteousness of saith among men. He, however, passed some years in his retirement at liis Brother's, in picus and useful ex- ercises, carrying his humility so far as to instruct youth at school; and died in 1429, aged 66.
